  [Text] Government spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis today said 
that yesterday, President Glavkos Kliridhis sent personal 
letters to U.S. President Bill Clinton and British Prime 
Minister John Major on the latest developments in the Cyprus 
issue and the continuing negotiations at the UN Security 
Council. Asked why the letters were sent to these two specific 
leaders, Kasoulidhis said the United States and Britain are the 
two powers that have recently moved toward the alternative of 
continuing the confidence-building measures [CBM's]. 
Kasoulidhis said: Kliridhis' letters aim to promote our side's 
positions. 
  Answering another question, the spokesman said Kliridhis' 
letter to Russian President Boris Yeltsin, which was conveyed by 
Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis during his visit in Moscow, 
had the same goal. The spokesman said meetings have been held 
on the same issue with France and China. 
  President Kliridhis and the foreign minister met the U.S. 
and 
British ambassadors in Nicosia. 

</TEXT>

