<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Dismisses Speculation on Health </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin Dismisses Speculation on Health </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0906084194 Hamburg DPA in German 0743 GMT 9 Jun 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0906084194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow (DPA) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin's unexpected trip to Mainz for a medical 
examination nourished speculation in Moscow on 9 June that he 
might resign before long. Two leading Moscow newspapers, 
KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA and NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA, citing 
unidentified circles, reported that Chernomyrdin was about to 
resign for health reasons. In that case, First Deputy Prime 
Minister Oleg Soskovets or former Russian Security Council 
Chairman Yuriy Skokov could succeed him. Chernomyrdin said in 
Germany, however, that he was in good health, and there were no 
indications that he might be weary of his position. 

</TEXT>

