<F P=100> CANADA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnia Warned Peacekeeping Forces May Be Withdrawn </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnia Warned Peacekeeping Forces May Be Withdrawn </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006212194 Montreal Radio Canada International in English 
2030 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1006212194 </F>
<F P=104>  Montreal Radio Canada International </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Canada has warned the Bosnian Government that it 
might withdraw its peacekeepers. Prime Minister Jean Chretien 
says Canada will scale back or cancel its peacekeeping effort if 
there is no progress toward peace or if the arms embargo on 
Bosnia is lifted. Mr. Chretien made the warning yesterday while 
visiting Canadian peacekeeping troops in Visoko, Bosnia. Canada 
has 800 soldiers there and another 1,100 in neighboring Croatia. 
  Mr. Chretien and other Western leaders discussed troop 
withdrawal earlier this week during D-Day ceremonies in France. 
He said a final decision on the peacekeeping force will be made 
in September when the Canadian peacekeeping mission expires. 
  The prime minister arrived home to Ottawa today after making 
the first ever visit to a war zone by a serving Canadian prime 
minister. Meanwhile, a one-month UN-sponsored cease-fire in 
Bosnia has gone into effect. 

</TEXT>

