<H3> <TI>   SPD Land Ministers Criticize Waigel Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SPD Land Ministers Criticize Waigel Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1006180194 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 10-11 Jun 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU1006180194 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed by "uhl": "Waigel: The Budget Will Be </F>
Consolidated Further"] 
  [Text] Bonn -- The finance ministers of the laender 
governed by the SPD [Social Democratic Party of Germany] have 
described the projected budget presented by Finance Minister 
Theo Waigel, Christian Social Union [CSU], for the years 1995-98 
as "unrealistic." What they have criticized above all is that 
the constitutionally necessary tax-free status of minimum 
incomes has not been considered and the fact that the Nuremberg 
Federal Office of Labor's budget is too low. 
  Waigel stressed that the government will firmly adhere to 
consolidating the budget over the next few years. The overall 
minimum expenditure that has been agreed for 1994 will be 
remain. Despite increasing signs of economic recovery, there is 
no basis for relaxing fiscal policy. CSU politicians have once 
again rejected an increase in taxes and dues. Johann Eekhoff, 
state secretary in the federal Economic Ministry, has reported 
that one can expect a increase in Germany's real economic growth 
of between 1.5 percent and 2.5 percent. An increase of about 3 
percent should be possible in the years 1995 to 1998. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

