<H3> <TI>   Lebanon's 'Awn Advocates Trilateral Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lebanon's 'Awn Advocates Trilateral Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1106220994 Paris Radio France International in French 2100 
GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1106220994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris today hosted the Lebanese National Congress, 
which supports General Michel 'Awn. Michel 'Awn has been living 
in exile in France for five years. He pledged not to express 
his views but he has not given up the idea of playing a 
political role in his country. He wants his country to stop 
being the hostage of the rather complicated relations between 
Syria and Israel. This is in substance what he said to Helene 
da Costa: 
  [Begin 'Awn recording] We are awaiting recommendations in 
order to get out of the stalemate in which Lebanon now finds 
itself and the peace negotiations with Israel because things at 
present are in a deadlock. Lebanon is totally signed away to 
Syria. It cannot do anything. It is there, but it is absent. 
  My proposals cannot be announced without being adopted [as 
heard] yet I advocate a change in the shape of the table. The 
table should not be bilateral, it should be trilateral: Syrian, 
Lebanese, and Israeli, because each of the two remaining forces 
claims to be in Lebanon because the other is there. If there are 
three of them, they cannot use this as a pretext. They must 
answer specific questions. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

