<H3> <TI>   European Elections Reportedly Won by Socialists </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    European Elections Reportedly Won by Socialists </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206172394 Lisbon RTP Internacional Television in 
Portuguese 1700 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1206172394 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon RTP Internacional Television </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Socialist Party [PS] has won the elections for 
the European Parliament in Portugal. The RTP/Catholic 
University forecast says that the Socialist Party won between 35 
and 39 percent of the vote, the Social Democratic Party [PSD] 
has won between 28 and 32 percent, the Social Democratic Center 
Party [CDS] has won between 12 and 14 percent of the vote, and 
Communist-Greens coalition [CDU] has between 9.5 and 11 percent 
of the vote. 
  This means that the PS has 11 MEP's [Member of European 
Parliament], PSD has eight MEP's, CDU has three MEP's, and the 
CDS has three MEP's. We will now compare these figures with 
those of the last European elections in 1989: The PS had 28.5 
percent, the PSD had 32.7 percent, the CDS had 14.2 percent, and 
the CDU had 14.4 percent. 

</TEXT>

