<DOCNO> FBIS4-43082 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu113_o_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-113 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mikhailidhis Leaves for UN Headquarters </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mikhailidhis Leaves for UN Headquarters </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1306113294 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1306113294 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis, who left 
Athens this morning for UN Headquarters, will begin 
consultations in New York on the Cyprus issue. Mr. Mikhailidhis 
will have contacts with UN Security Council members and will 
meet with UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali on Thursday 
[16 June]. 
  Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias will also be 
visiting New York and Mr. Mikhailidhis will have a meeting with 
him to coordinate actions. Mr. Mikhailidhis will also have 
contacts in Washington with leading U.S. State Department 
officials and with members of Congress. [passage omitted] 
Government spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis has stressed that the 
role of the five Security Council permanent members is to 
strengthen the UN secretary general's efforts and not to be a 
substitute for him. 
  Responding to a correspondent's question on Rauf Denktas' 
demand that the Robert Lamb ideas be incorporated into the 21 
March document, Mr. Kasoulidhis said that there cannot be any 
Lamb ideas and pointed out that, according to the secretary 
general's mandate of good offices, those who can submit ideas 
and discuss ideas at the negotiating table are the secretary 
general and his representatives. 

</TEXT>

