<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   REUTER Cited on Kliridhis Resignation Report </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    REUTER Cited on Kliridhis Resignation Report </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1006203994 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 2000 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1006203994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] REUTER reported tonight that President Glavkos 
Kliridhis has said he will resign and proclaim presidential 
elections at end of October if the UN Security Council decides 
to continue talks on the confidence-building measures [CBM's]. 
REUTER added that President Kliridhis outlines this position in 
letters to U.S. President Bill Clinton and British Prime 
Minister John Major. 
  According to the letters, copies of which REUTER claims to 
have obtained, President Kliridhis notes that the new president, 
who would be free from the committments Mr. Kliridhis has 
undertaken, would have to decide on the CBM's issue. 
  Government Spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis announced today 
that 
President Kliridhis sent letters to President Clinton and Prime 
Minister John Major. Mr. Kasoulidhis said that the letters aim 
at promoting our side's positions and pointed out that the 
United States and Britain are the two powers who recently moved 
in the direction of continuing the CBM's process. 
  In a statement to CyBC [Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation] 
tonight, the government spokesman reiterated his statement from 
yesterday saying he does not know of President Kliridhis' 
intention to resign and added that he is not aware of the 
content of the letters. 

</TEXT>

