Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Turkey </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Involvement Denied </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Involvement Denied </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1206190994 Paris AFP in English 1804 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1206190994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nicosia, June 12 (AFP) -- Sixteen Iranian 
asylum-seekers facing expulsion from Turkey are not members of 
the armed opposition People's Mujahedin, the group said Sunday 
[12 June]. 
  "The persons in question are not in any way related to the 
Mujahedeen and its activities," it said in a statement sent to 
AFP in Nicosia. 
  "The Government of Turkey is responsible for the protection 
and safety of all Iranian asylum-seekers," the group said, a day 
after the Turkish news agency ANATOLIA said they were being 
expelled to Iraq. 
  "If for whatever reason it does not wish to accept them, it 
must relocate them in European countries with the help of the 
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees," said the 
Mujahedeen. 
  It said the group had helped the 16 Iranians seek refuge in 
Turkey for humanitarian reasons only. They had been living in 
Ramadi, west of Baghdad, and some had been POWs during the 
1980-1988 war between Iran and Iraq. 
  But ANATOLIA said the 16 had confessed to having entered 
Turkey with false passports and received military training at a 
Mujahedin camp in Iraq. 
  The Turkish Interior Ministry rejected their request for 
political asylum and drove them to Silopi on the Iraqi border, 
it reported, quoting a senior police official as saying the 
expulsion was a goodwill gesture to Iran. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

