<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Begins Meetings in New York </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Begins Meetings in New York </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1406071494 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 0430 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1406071494 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis began his talks 
on the Cyprus issue in New York by meeting with the UN secretary 
general's senior adviser. Today, Mikhailidhis will have 
successive talks with the representatives of the 15 UN Security 
Council member states and Alternate UN Secretary General Marrack 
Goulding. 
  In a statement to the Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation 
correspondent in New York, the foreign minister said that a new 
report by UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali is 
unjustified and will set a bad precedence. He added that the 
recent talks between Gustave Feissel, the UN secretary general's 
alternate special representative in Cyprus, and Turkish Cypriot 
leader Rauf Denktas do not justify the issuing of a new report. 
  Referring to the telephone conversation between U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher and President Glavkos 
Kliridhis, Mikhailidhis said that the call was designed to 
encourage efforts on the confidence-building measures procedure 
to continue. Discussing the U.S. position, Mikhailidhis 
rejected claims that Cyprus-U.S. relations are being disturbed, 
describing them as relations of continuous and close 
communication. 
  Mikhailidhis will meet the UN secretary general on Thursday 
[16 June]. It has not yet been decided whether he will go to 
Washington for talks with U.S. State Department officials. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

