<H3> <TI>   Daily Claims Confidence Measures `Dead' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Daily Claims Confidence Measures `Dead' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1306112394 Nicosia ELEVTHEROTIPIA TIS DHEVTERAS in Greek 
13 Jun 94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> NC1306112394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia ELEVTHEROTIPIA TIS DHEVTERAS </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Views" column: "A Made Decision"] </F>
  [Text] President Glavkos Kliridhis' decision to resign if 
the British and Americans pressure the UN Security Council and 
the UN secretary general to continue the process of the 
so-called confidence-building measures should not be 
misinterpreted by the Foreign Office and the State Department. 
  The Cyprus Government cannot threaten. However, it has the 
right to protest and warn against the consequences of the 
criminal policy being followed by the governments of the two 
countries. 
  The confidence-building measures are dead, even if Hurd, 
Christopher, and Cetin do not want to accept this reality. Our 
side's appraisal of the confidence-building measures is also 
supported by the secretary general, his representatives, and 
even by members of the Security Council. It is only the United 
States and Britain who do not want to be convinced and are 
actually plotting to undermine the Government of the Republic of 
Cyprus, which they allegedly recognize, to satisfy the desires 
of Ankara. 
  The press reports that the contents of Kliridhis' letters 
was 
leaked out by the U.S. Embassy in Nicosia prove the coarse 
policy that Washington wants to impose. However, it must have 
realized that the decision to terminate the confidence-building 
measures has already been made. No substantial results will be 
achieved by the scandalous and provocative U.S. and British 
behavior to drag us once again into procedures that have served 
the Turkish side's intransigent tactics and filibustering. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

