<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Repercussions of U.S. Recommendations Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Repercussions of U.S. Recommendations Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1206115894 Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA in Greek 11 Jun 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> NC1206115894 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [The "Views" column: "Toward Dialogue"] </F>
  [Text] What would the prerequisites be for a meeting 
between Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou and Turkish Prime 
Minister Tansu Ciller, when it appears to be prepared with the 
Greek side showing "goodwill" and the Turkish side continuing 
its provocations and intransigence? 
  Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias said that a meeting 
"would 
be desirable only if it would create a good climate." But could 
this good climate be created given the U.S. position, which is 
openly in support of Turkey as can be seen from the 
"recommendations" made only to Greece? 
  Could obedience to "suggestions" and "recommendations" lead 
to subjection and an outcome that would be against us on 
critical national issues? 
  According to accurate ELEVTHEROTIPIA information, the 
"recommendations" toward Greece are: a) to show "goodwill," 
understanding, and moderation in the approach to Turkey by 
putting aside the Cyprus issue, b) to show generosity toward 
Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] as a 
strong power in the Balkans and c) not to consider the United 
States an alternative for solutions on which we can depend, 
given that we belong to the European Union [EU]. 
  Interpreting and complying with these "recommendations" 
cannot bring results favorable to the national interest. 
Unless--as we stressed yesterday--Papandreou is aware of things 
that other Greeks--people, parties, and press--do not know about. 
  But, is it correct and nationally useful not to be aware of 
what is being played--if it is being played--under the table? 
Where can secret diplomacy, which Papandreou criticized when he 
was in the opposition, lead? 
  The facts of the public aspects of our national issues, as 
well as recent Turkish provocation--with U.S. encouragement--do 
not allow for any reasonable optimism. 
  On the contrary, they raise a number of concerned questions 
about what may happen if we get involved in "goodwill" moves, 
which will essentially mean subjection, after following the 
recommendations. Therefore, open answers and open diplomacy are 
needed because citizens have a right to know. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-43198 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu114_q_94003" </HT>


