<H3> <TI>   `Good Relations' To Be </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Good Relations' To Be </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
`Strengthened' 

<F P=102>   TA1406060394 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 2100 
GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1406060394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Tansu Ciller has received Iranian 
Interior Minister 'Ali Mohammad Besharati-Jahromi, who is in 
Turkey on an official visit. Murat Karayalcin, state minister 
and deputy prime minister, and Interior Minister Nahit Mentese 
were also present at the meeting. Ambassador Volkan Vural, the 
prime minister's adviser, said in a statement to reporters that 
during the meeting Ciller stressed the importance Turkey 
attaches to its friendship and cooperation with Iran. Vural 
said: At the meeting, Besharati reiterated that Iran will never 
allow activities against Turkey to take place on its territory. 
He added that the issues of joint operations and an exchange of 
terrorists were not discussed at the Ciller-Besharati meeting. 
  Besharati later called on Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin. At 
the meeting, Cetin said that the good relations between the two 
friendly and neighborly countries greatly contribute to regional 
stability. Cetin added that the good bilateral relations will be 
further strengthened through high-level dialogues. Besharati 
said that no group will be allowed to engage in activities 
against Turkey on Iranian territory. He added that President 
Suleyman Demirel's visit to Tehran next month will be an 
important step in bilateral relations. Mentese was also present 
at the Cetin-Besharati meeting. 
  Speaking to reporters after his meeting with Cetin, 
Besharati 
said that Turkey and Iran share the view that the disruption of 
Iraq's territorial integrity will endanger regional stability. 
Replying to correspondents' questions, Mentese said that there 
are no border disputes between Iran and Turkey and that the 
issue of border security was discussed. In reply to a question 
on whether Besharati was informed of Turkey's expectations 
regarding border security, Mentese said: We have jointly 
included the issue of PKK [Workers Party of Kurdistan] terror on 
the agenda. We are discussing the issue. Iran has also 
accepted that the PKK is a terror organization. In any event, 
Iran agrees that there is no Kurdish problem in Turkey and that 
the PKK is a terror organization. 

</TEXT>

