<H3> <TI>   Cetin, Netherland's Kooijmans Discuss Terrorism </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cetin, Netherland's Kooijmans Discuss Terrorism </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1006182194 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1505 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1006182194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Istanbul, June 10 (A.A.) -- Foreign Minister Hikmet 
Cetin said on Friday [10 June] that the Netherlands struggled 
against terrorism within its legal framework adding that it 
tried to prevent terrorism activities. 
  Cetin met Dutch Foreign Minister Peter Kooijmans during the 
North Atlantic Cooperation Council meetings and said Dutch laws 
did not ban an organization or an association which is not 
directly involved in a violation. 
  `Kooijmans conveyed that they are obviously taking 
additional 
measures and they struggle with possible terrorism activities 
that could come from other sides of Europe,' Cetin said. 
  `Kooijmans said there were reported ones who are under 
custody and some of them were extradited. They stressed 
importance to preventing terrorism activities rather than 
banning,' he added. 
  Cetin said European friends and allies should give support 
to 
Turkey on terrorism adding that giving this support is an 
international obligation. 
  He also said they discussed developments in the European 
Union [EU] and Turkish-EU relations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

