<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Says Inspectors in DPRK `Pursuing Mission' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA Says Inspectors in DPRK `Pursuing Mission' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1306133694 Paris AFP in English 1256 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1306133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, June 13 (AFP) -- Two inspectors from the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) were pursuing their 
mission in North Korea normally Monday [13 June], following 
early threats by Pyongyang authorities to expel them, IAEA 
spokesman David Kyd said. 
  He said the Agency had received no word from North Korean 
authorities Monday, which led IAEA officials to believe that 
"for the time being" there was no reason to think the inspectors 
would be expelled. 
  Yun Ho-chin, spokesman for Pyongyang's Vienna embassy, said 
Friday North Korea would take "adequate retaliatory measures" 
following an IAEA vote that day to suspend technical aid to 
North Korea in an escalating row over North Korea's refusal to 
meet international demands for inspection of its nuclear 
facilities. 
  Yun said that North Korea's retaliatary measures could 
include the expulsion of IAEA inspectors from North Korea, a ban 
on all verification procedures, and a possible withdrawal of 
North Korea from the IAEA and the Nuclear Non-Proliferation 
Treaty. 
  But Kyd said no official message had reached the IAEA 
headquarters and its two inspectors were currently observing 
8,000 spent fuel rods removed from the 5-megawatt Yongbyon 
experimental nuclear reactor. 
  The inspectors were not allowed to take samples from the 
rods. 
  The IAEA and Washington believe that Pyongyang has 
restricted 
the inspection of the reactor in order to conceal alleged 
diversion of nuclear material to an atomic weapons programme. 
  Kyd said last Friday's IAEA resolution condemning North 
Korea 
for refusing to abide by its safeguards had been forwarded to 
the UN Security Council. 
  He added that he expected the analysis of samples taken in 
May from a radio-chemical laboratory at Yongbyon to be available 
by the end of June. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

