<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Majority Trusts Berlusconi </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Shows Majority Trusts Berlusconi </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1506103194 Rome LA REPUBBLICA in Italian 14 Jun p 10 </F>
<F P=103> BR1506103194 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome LA REPUBBLICA </F>
<F P=105>  Italian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "DOXA: 66 Percent of Italians Trust </F>
the Head of Government"] 
  [Text] Rome -- Sixty-six percent of the Italians trust 
Silvio Berlusconi as prime minister, according to a poll taken 
by DOXA prior to the European elections and published only 
yesterday. Those interviewed said that they had "a lot" (27 
percent) or "sufficient" (39 percent) trust in the present head 
of the government, who in this way achieved an approval rating 
of 66 percent. Eleven percent of those interviewed had no trust 
in him and 18 percent "little," a dissapproval rating of 29 
percent. This makes Berlusconi the prime minister who, since 
1992, has inspired most trust in Italians. Previously Carlo 
Azeglio Ciampi achieved a 60 percent approval rating in May 
1993, which fell however to 51 percent in September and 49 
percent in January of this year. 

</TEXT>

