<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman: Kliridhis Resignation Decision `Personal' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman: Kliridhis Resignation Decision `Personal' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1406143394 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1400 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1406143394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Government Spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis described 
President Glavkos Kliridhis' decision to resign if the UN 
Security Council continues discussion of the confidence-building 
measures, as a strictly personal choice. President Kliridhis, 
the spokesman said, weighed the developments very seriously 
before reaching this decision and decided if resigning from the 
presidency would make the future of Cypriot Hellenism easier, he 
would not hesitate to do so. Responding to a question, the 
government spokesman said that if the president resigns, he 
would not seek the presidency again. Kasoulidhis also said that 
if President Kliridhis resigns and calls for new elections, the 
elections would be a popular mandate on a specific issue. 
  Kasoulidhis also said that there has been no reaction from 
the United States or Britain to the letter that President 
Kliridhis sent to President Bill Clinton and Prime Minister John 
Major. The spokesman refused to reveal the contents of the 
letter, saying the letter was confidential. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

