<H3> <TI>   Papoulias: Government `Firm' on Sovereign Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Papoulias: Government `Firm' on Sovereign Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1406203294 Athens ET-1 Television Network in Greek 1800 
GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1406203294 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ET-1 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shortly before his departure from Ioannina for 
Athens today, Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias stressed that 
Greece continues to defend its national sovereign rights in the 
Aegean. Replying to correspondents' questions, Papoulias once 
again expressed opposition to the dispatch of Turkish troops to 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  [Begin Papoulias recording] Greece has always defended its 
national sovereign rights in the Aegean and this position has 
not changed, whether it concerns the state power for the 
extension [of territorial waters] to 12 miles, or the air space, 
where Greece's positions have been firm since the first PASOK 
[Panhellenic Socialist Movement] government. Engaging Balkan 
powers in the massacre of the former Yugoslavia causes 
additional problems instead of alleviating the situation. The 
presence of Turkish forces in Bonsia-Herzegovina indeed makes 
things more difficult and, I believe, particularly causes more 
tension in the inter-Balkan relations. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

