  [Text] During a meeting in Athens today between the 
defense ministers of Greece and Cyprus, Yerasimos Arsenis and 
Konstandinos Iliadhistoward, significant decisions were made 
toward a joint defense doctrine between Greece and Cyprus. 
Details regarding the joint defense doctrine were announced 
after the two defense ministers met in Nicosia last March. 
Today's talks between Arsenis and Iliadhis lasted for three 
hours. They agreed to hold joint military exercises between the 
Greek Armed Forces and the Cypriot National Guard, and construct 
infrastructure projects to promote cooperation between the 
airforce and navy of Greece and Cyprus. 

