<H3> <TI>   Spokesman on Relations With Greece, Aegean Flights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman on Relations With Greece, Aegean Flights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1506104194 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1000 
GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1506104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] It has been announced that Turkey has always been 
careful to refrain from actions that could cause tension in its 
relations with Greece. In reply to a question during his weekly 
news conference today, Foreign Ministry Spokesman Ferhat Ataman 
said the straining of relations between Turkey and Greece will 
not serve the interests of either country. Ataman recalled that 
during the NATO foreign ministers meeting held in Istanbul, the 
Greek foreign minister informed Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin 
that he shares Turkey's stand on this issue and will be pleased 
to see it implemented. Within this framework, Ataman stressed, 
Turkish planes flew over the Aegean without weapons for some 
time. 
  Ataman continued: This gesture on the part of Turkey has not 
been reciprocated yet. This is extremely important, in that it 
sheds light on the Greek attitude. Under these circumstances, 
it is natural for us to take the measures we deem necessary in 
line with the flight security and operational needs of our 
planes. 

</TEXT>

