<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cetin Supports Extension </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cetin Supports Extension </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1406180494 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1535 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1406180494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, June 14 (A.A.) -- Foreign Minister Hikmet 
Cetin on Tuesday [14 June] said that the extension of the 
mandate for the multinational force is in Turkey's advantage, 
adding in case they are moved out the terrorist PKK [Workers 
Party of Kurdistan] organization will have a wider freedom of 
movement in the region. 
  He was speaking at the parliamentarian general council 
meeting where the issue concerning its extension for another six 
months as of June 30 is being discussed. 
  He said it is not a force that has been set up against 
Turkey's will, reminding it was set up initially upon Turkey's 
request in 1991, in conformity with Article 192 of the Turkish 
Constitution. 
  `The terrorist PKK organization is the one who is the most 
against the force. Because if it is dismantled they will have 
an extraordinary freedom of movement in a troubled region. If 
it is lifted Turkey will also lose its support for the fight 
against terrorism in the southeast,' he said. 
  He said the problems in that region do not stem from the 
force but from the embargo imposed on northern Iraq. 
  `Even if the force goes, as long as the embargo is on, 
problems will continue,' he said adding that Iraq's territorial 
integrity is of a great importance to Turkey. 

</TEXT>

